	<div id="comment_top_65267733" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_65267733" name="comment_link_65267733" href="//yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23649913&amp;cid=65267733" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(65267733)" >Re:It's a private company</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_65267733" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 65267733); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>5</a>, Insightful)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~rocket+rancher">rocket rancher</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~rocket+rancher">( 447670 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_65267733">		 &lt;<a href="mailto:themovingfinger%40gmail.com">themovingfinger@gmail.com</a>&gt;
		on Saturday March 29, 2025 @10:26AM (<span class="ind"></span><a rel="nofollow" href="//yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23649913&amp;cid=65267733">#65267733</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65267733"><p><div class="quote"><p>So they can ban him for any reason they want; he has no right to their services.  Freedom of speech only applies to the government.</p><p>Or at least this is what you would hear a couple of years ago when people were being banned from public forums or social media for conservative viewpoints.  I guess suddenly it really is a terrible injustice for a private company to ban someone for private company reasons.</p></div><p>So let me get this straight &mdash; your comment isn&rsquo;t about the article or the actual issue raised. It&rsquo;s a lazy culture war potshot. Instead of engaging with the disturbing use of facial recognition and blacklists by MSG to punish a guy over a years-old T-shirt design, you&rsquo;re trying to score points by invoking a completely unrelated grievance: conservative voices on social media.</p><p>Here&rsquo;s the problem with that: those bans you&rsquo;re alluding to? In nearly every case, they weren&rsquo;t for holding conservative views. They were for violating platform rules &mdash; doxxing, harassment, incitement, spreading disinformation. It wasn&rsquo;t about what they believed, but how they expressed it. You&rsquo;re equating shouting &ldquo;fire&rdquo; in a crowded theater with disagreeing about fire codes.</p><p>And that distinction matters &mdash; just like it matters here. Frank Miller wasn&rsquo;t disruptive. He wasn&rsquo;t wearing the shirt. He hadn&rsquo;t even been to an MSG event in decades. He was silently identified, tracked, and banned by a corporate surveillance system &mdash; not for his behavior, but for designing a satirical shirt years ago and being tagged in a social media post. That is not about free speech, left vs. right, or platform moderation. That&rsquo;s about surveillance creep, arbitrary corporate punishment, and the normalization of facial recognition as a tool to silence dissent.</p><p>If you actually cared about civil liberties &mdash; instead of just lobbing predictable &ldquo;gotchas&rdquo; &mdash; you&rsquo;d see this is exactly the kind of thing everyone should be concerned about, regardless of political leaning. But you&rsquo;re not here for the principles. You&rsquo;re here to troll and posture.  Go troll somewhere else.</p></div>
	</div>

